WEBVTT

00:01.585 --> 00:02.753
[ Animal calls ]

00:02.753 --> 00:05.172
Okay. 9:14 p. m.

00:05.172 --> 00:06.882
I should have ended the survey
after this morning,

00:06.882 --> 00:08.509
but, uh, thank God I didn't.

00:08.509 --> 00:11.220
[ Animal howls in distance ]

00:11.220 --> 00:14.973
All the hard work and sacrifice
has finally paid off.

00:14.973 --> 00:17.142
I found it.
Indisputable proof.

00:17.142 --> 00:19.978
[ Branch snaps ]
Is anyone there?

00:19.978 --> 00:25.776
♪♪

00:25.776 --> 00:27.569
Hello!

00:27.569 --> 00:30.239
Is anyone there?

00:30.239 --> 00:31.823
Hello?

00:31.823 --> 00:33.283
[ Creature growling ]

00:33.283 --> 00:35.118
It found me.

00:37.621 --> 00:39.665
I-It found me!

00:39.665 --> 00:42.584
[ Grunting ]

00:42.584 --> 00:44.378
Oh, God!

00:46.255 --> 00:47.172
[ Whimpers ]

00:49.341 --> 00:51.718
[ Whispers ]
Ellen, if you see this,

00:51.718 --> 00:53.512
know that I've always loved you.

00:53.512 --> 00:55.806
I-I don't know why
I didn't say that before.

00:55.806 --> 00:59.643
God, I do not want to die,
do not want to die.

00:59.643 --> 01:01.520
[ Insects chirping ]

01:04.231 --> 01:06.024
Okay.

01:11.280 --> 01:12.823
[ Breathing shakily ]

01:12.823 --> 01:14.157
[ Creature roars ]

01:14.157 --> 01:15.617
[ Grunts ]

01:15.617 --> 01:18.579
[ Screams ]

01:18.579 --> 01:23.292
♪♪

01:25.127 --> 01:26.545
[ Cellphone chimes ]

01:26.545 --> 01:28.922
Morning, Daddy.
Did you sleep okay?

01:28.922 --> 01:31.466
Greg: You know, you called me
a lot of things in high school.

01:31.466 --> 01:33.385
But Daddy?

01:33.385 --> 01:35.679
What the hell?
What are you doing here?

01:35.679 --> 01:36.805
Oh, hey, Simone.

01:36.805 --> 01:38.890
You remember Greg Wright
from Fairfax High?

01:38.890 --> 01:41.310
How could I forget
my nemesis?

01:41.310 --> 01:43.562
Your nemesis?
Oh, no, never that.

01:43.562 --> 01:46.481
I was just the man
that beat you for valedictorian.

01:46.481 --> 01:49.234
To beat me implies
that you were better.

01:49.234 --> 01:51.320
But we had
the exact same GPA.

01:51.320 --> 01:53.363
Why are you here?
Why is he here?

01:53.363 --> 01:54.990
Greg's my CPA.

01:54.990 --> 01:57.534
He does the books
for my nonprofit.

01:57.534 --> 02:00.120
Time's been good to you,
Simone.

02:00.120 --> 02:01.246
You look very happy.

02:01.246 --> 02:02.706
Thank you.

02:02.706 --> 02:05.459
Don't forget that part.
You see it.

02:05.459 --> 02:07.169
So how about you and I
have a proper catch-up?

02:07.169 --> 02:09.504
Maybe some lunch, coffee?

02:09.504 --> 02:10.630
My treat, of course.

02:10.630 --> 02:13.133
Hey, take your eyes
off my daughter

02:13.133 --> 02:15.302
and put your eyes back
on my books.

02:15.302 --> 02:16.845
You're on the clock here.

02:16.845 --> 02:18.347
[ Cellphone ringing ]
Yes, sir.

02:18.347 --> 02:20.182
Back on the books.
He told you.

02:20.182 --> 02:22.559
[ Chuckles ]

02:22.559 --> 02:24.061
Hey, boss.

02:26.313 --> 02:29.441
You want --
You want me to go where?

02:29.441 --> 02:32.402
Carter:
The Angeles National Forest.

02:32.402 --> 02:34.946
600,000 acres
of wilderness.

02:34.946 --> 02:37.240
And bug bites.

02:38.659 --> 02:41.370
You've got an Oakwood Racer kit
in your car?

02:41.370 --> 02:42.621
Is Isaiah a Scout?

02:42.621 --> 02:44.289
Yeah,
and he needs to make a car

02:44.289 --> 02:46.291
for the annual race
this weekend.

02:46.291 --> 02:49.127
Why is it in your car, then,
and not in his backpack?

02:49.127 --> 02:50.379
'Cause he hates
making them.

02:50.379 --> 02:51.838
Waits till
the last minute,

02:51.838 --> 02:53.507
then he's bummed
when he doesn't win.

02:53.507 --> 02:56.134
You know you don't teach
your kids anything

02:56.134 --> 02:57.636
by doing their homework
for them.

02:57.636 --> 02:59.638
In school, yes,
but this is the Scouts.

02:59.638 --> 03:02.015
It ain't about the kids.
It's dad vs. dad.

03:02.015 --> 03:03.266
[ Chuckles ]
And I'm competing
against

03:03.266 --> 03:06.520
literal rocket scientists
from JPL.

03:06.520 --> 03:09.314
With the divorce,
I'm just showing him I care.

03:09.314 --> 03:10.941
[ Whispering ]
Showing him how to cheat.

03:10.941 --> 03:12.984
What was that?
[ Normal voice ] Huh?

03:12.984 --> 03:15.529
No, I just said
these trees are so pretty.

03:15.529 --> 03:24.246
♪♪

03:24.246 --> 03:26.331
Garza: Over here.

03:26.331 --> 03:27.833
Morning.

03:27.833 --> 03:30.502
We are working
a missing persons today.

03:30.502 --> 03:32.796
Must be someone important
for it to wind up in our laps.

03:32.796 --> 03:33.964
It is, and then some.

03:33.964 --> 03:35.924
We're doing a favor
for Senator Smith.

03:35.924 --> 03:38.385
You mean Senator Smith who is
neither a senator nor a Smith?

03:38.385 --> 03:41.012
Come on, once and for all,
just tell us who he is.

03:41.012 --> 03:43.390
A high-ranking guardian angel
who has asked us

03:43.390 --> 03:46.685
to investigate the disappearance
of Wallace Yamashiro,

03:46.685 --> 03:48.562
an assistant director
at DARPA.

03:48.562 --> 03:50.814
Now, Wallace has been vital
in developing

03:50.814 --> 03:54.276
top-secret technologies used
to advance national security.

03:54.276 --> 03:57.404
So maybe he got snatched up
because somebody wanted

03:57.404 --> 03:59.489
the secrets
in that big old brain of his.

03:59.489 --> 04:01.366
Bingo. We're looking
at his campsite here

04:01.366 --> 04:02.742
where he disappeared
two nights ago

04:02.742 --> 04:03.618
while doing research.

04:03.618 --> 04:04.995
On what?

04:04.995 --> 04:05.912
That's not important,
Brendon.

04:05.912 --> 04:07.747
It kinda is.

04:07.747 --> 04:10.000
I mean, if we knew
what he was looking for,

04:10.000 --> 04:12.377
it could give us a clue
on where to search for him.

04:12.377 --> 04:14.129
She's right.

04:14.129 --> 04:17.382
Well, besides being
a certified genius,

04:17.382 --> 04:20.260
Wallace liked to spend his spare
time searching for Bigfoot.

04:20.260 --> 04:23.180
[ Laughs ]

04:24.514 --> 04:27.100
Oh, you're serious.

04:27.100 --> 04:28.226
There's something
you should see.

04:29.895 --> 04:31.229
Definite signs
of a struggle.

04:31.229 --> 04:34.524
Yeah, that's dried blood.
He was attacked.

04:34.524 --> 04:38.028
Question is, was it human
or humanoid?

04:38.028 --> 04:40.989
You are not suggesting
Bigfoot did this.

04:40.989 --> 04:43.200
I'm saying we should leave
our options open.

04:46.411 --> 04:48.330
We got a camera.

04:48.330 --> 04:50.290
Please tell me it still works
and has footage

04:50.290 --> 04:52.209
of what happened
to Wallace on it.

04:52.209 --> 04:54.252
Mm. No, it's toast.

04:54.252 --> 04:56.463
Yeah, the memory card
is cracked in two.

04:56.463 --> 04:58.423
I can take it to the tech lab,
see what they can do.

04:58.423 --> 05:00.300
Alright.

05:00.300 --> 05:03.220
Simone: Uh, guys.

05:03.220 --> 05:05.430
Tell me this is not
what I think it is.

05:05.430 --> 05:06.723
Mm-hmm.

05:06.723 --> 05:09.142
Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

05:10.727 --> 05:12.729
Yeah.

05:12.729 --> 05:14.147
Since you're
headed back,

05:14.147 --> 05:15.732
have the lab
take a look at this.

05:15.732 --> 05:18.819
Carter, you know this is bear
or coyote, right?

05:18.819 --> 05:21.279
I agree,
but might as well be sure.

05:22.864 --> 05:25.367
Alright. I gotta go meet up
with the SAC.

05:25.367 --> 05:27.494
Join up
with the search team.

05:27.494 --> 05:28.662
If the rangers find
any evidence,

05:28.662 --> 05:29.830
I want the two of you
on it first.

05:33.208 --> 05:35.168
There was a --
There was a bug on you.

05:36.211 --> 05:38.213
[ Elevator bell dings ]

05:38.213 --> 05:42.050
By the way...
happy birthday.

05:42.050 --> 05:44.177
What?
How did you find out?

05:44.177 --> 05:46.012
I'm a professional
investigator.

05:46.012 --> 05:47.347
[ Scoffs ]

05:47.347 --> 05:48.473
Elena told me.

05:48.473 --> 05:49.391
Yeah.

05:49.391 --> 05:51.142
Here.

05:51.142 --> 05:53.812
Brendon,
I'm your training agent.

05:53.812 --> 05:55.230
You didn't need
to get me a present.

05:55.230 --> 05:57.023
And yet I did.

05:57.023 --> 05:59.234
And I'll bet
you can't guess what it is.

05:59.234 --> 06:00.902
Oh, um, okay.

06:00.902 --> 06:02.612
Uh...

06:02.612 --> 06:04.322
A platinum Montblanc pen.

06:04.322 --> 06:06.074
What?

06:06.074 --> 06:07.284
How'd you guess that?

06:07.284 --> 06:08.785
I got it right?
Yeah.

06:08.785 --> 06:09.452
Really?
Yeah.

06:09.452 --> 06:10.704
Wow.

06:10.704 --> 06:12.080
Gosh, I'm good.

06:12.080 --> 06:13.790
Uh, size of the box,
really.

06:13.790 --> 06:15.375
That kinda gave it away.

06:15.375 --> 06:16.835
You know,
couldn't be jewelry

06:16.835 --> 06:19.921
'cause you're desperate to
impress, but you're not crazy.

06:19.921 --> 06:21.423
So, pen. Yeah.
And you have money.

06:21.423 --> 06:23.633
So you went with the most
high-end one, Montblanc.

06:23.633 --> 06:25.635
Thanks for the gift.

06:25.635 --> 06:26.553
What are you doing?

06:26.553 --> 06:27.971
You can't have it
anymore.

06:27.971 --> 06:29.890
Why not?
Because I'm
a renowned gift giver,

06:29.890 --> 06:31.016
and people love my gifts

06:31.016 --> 06:32.434
because they're thoughtful
and surprising.

06:32.434 --> 06:34.060
And you guessed mine,
which means I failed.

06:34.060 --> 06:35.604
And I don't like failing.

06:35.604 --> 06:37.147
So I'll get you something else.
Don't worry about it.

06:37.147 --> 06:38.315
No,
I really want the pen.

06:38.315 --> 06:39.107
You can't have it.

06:39.107 --> 06:40.859
Go deliver
the evidence.

06:44.779 --> 06:47.490
Brendon: Hey.
Promise not to laugh at me?

06:47.490 --> 06:50.660
Could you please run this fur
for me?

06:50.660 --> 06:52.662
What am I looking for
evidence of?

06:52.662 --> 06:53.705
Bigfoot.

06:53.705 --> 06:55.373
Good one.

06:56.958 --> 06:57.959
That wasn't a joke?

06:57.959 --> 06:59.753
Uh, no.

07:01.171 --> 07:04.341
So, did you enjoy the bottle
of Syrah I gave you?

07:04.341 --> 07:06.217
Yea-- Yeah.

07:06.217 --> 07:09.220
No, uh, I haven't, uh,
opened it yet,

07:09.220 --> 07:12.265
but...thank you again.

07:12.265 --> 07:14.267
Let me know
when you try it.

07:14.267 --> 07:15.727
I want a full report.

07:18.563 --> 07:22.776
Y-Yeah. You know,
I-I-I'm actually not really

07:22.776 --> 07:26.237
like a --
like a wine guy.

07:26.237 --> 07:29.157
But you said you had a bottle
before and loved it.

07:29.157 --> 07:30.200
I did.

07:30.200 --> 07:32.202
But it was such
a thoughtful gift

07:32.202 --> 07:35.372
that I figured someone
should appreciate it fully.

07:35.372 --> 07:37.749
And so I-I have a-a friend
who I-I passed it to.

07:37.749 --> 07:39.876
You gave away my gift.

07:39.876 --> 07:41.169
Dieu aide moi.

07:41.169 --> 07:43.213
Uh...
see, Antoinette --

07:43.213 --> 07:45.048
No. Talking's over.

07:45.048 --> 07:48.510
I have to waste my time
testing for Bigfoot DNA.

07:50.011 --> 07:52.764
You don't really believe in
all this Yeti business, do you?

07:52.764 --> 07:54.432
Yetis are Himalayan.

07:54.432 --> 07:56.309
On the West Coast, the creatures
are called Sasquatch,

07:56.309 --> 07:57.727
Bigfoot, or Skookum.

07:57.727 --> 08:01.022
That's a lot of names
for something totally made up.

08:01.022 --> 08:04.401
I mean, you're mister
"all about the facts,"

08:04.401 --> 08:06.903
and when it comes to Bigfoot,
there's no proof.

08:06.903 --> 08:08.738
Well, there's not
not proof, either.

08:08.738 --> 08:11.199
Basically every indigenous
culture on the Pacific Coast

08:11.199 --> 08:13.535
has stories of a large
ape-like creature.

08:13.535 --> 08:15.704
Ranger, you out here
every day.

08:15.704 --> 08:17.455
You ever seen
the Skookum?

08:17.455 --> 08:20.917
No, but I've seen a lot
of strange things out here,

08:20.917 --> 08:23.461
so, you know,
it's entirely possible.

08:24.921 --> 08:26.297
It's not
that farfetched.

08:26.297 --> 08:28.717
Scientists have discovered
dozens of new species

08:28.717 --> 08:29.801
this year alone.

08:29.801 --> 08:31.636
Yeah. Lizards, bugs,

08:31.636 --> 08:34.556
crazy-looking fish
on the bottom of the ocean.

08:34.556 --> 08:38.017
Not big, hairy freaks
traipsing through the forest.

08:38.017 --> 08:40.228
[ Grunting, wheezing ]
Carter.

08:40.228 --> 08:41.438
Yeah.

08:41.438 --> 08:43.106
You heard that, right?

08:43.106 --> 08:44.649
Yeah.

08:44.649 --> 08:47.152
No, no, no.
D-Don't go towards it.

08:47.152 --> 08:51.239
♪♪

08:51.239 --> 08:53.742
That's Wallace's
backpack.

08:53.742 --> 08:54.909
FBI. Stop.

08:54.909 --> 08:56.077
Show us your hands.

08:57.662 --> 08:59.080
Stop. FBI.

09:00.623 --> 09:03.501
[ Grunts, wheezing ]

09:03.501 --> 09:04.753
What's wrong with him?

09:04.753 --> 09:07.464
Is he okay?

09:07.464 --> 09:10.258
Dr. Cooper: It's acute
radiation syndrome.

09:10.258 --> 09:11.676
That doesn't sound good.

09:11.676 --> 09:12.969
It's not.

09:12.969 --> 09:14.304
Any idea
where he was exposed?

09:14.304 --> 09:16.347
We found him
in the Angeles Forest.

09:16.347 --> 09:19.184
He has minor cutaneous
radiation injuries.

09:19.184 --> 09:21.352
Burns on his skin.

09:21.352 --> 09:24.773
So the radiation
was probably airborne.

09:24.773 --> 09:27.484
Whoa. D-Does that mean
that we were exposed?

09:27.484 --> 09:29.736
We were only out there
for a few hours.

09:29.736 --> 09:31.946
You should be okay.

09:31.946 --> 09:34.115
But I'll get you prescriptions
for potassium iodide

09:34.115 --> 09:36.493
as a precaution.

09:36.493 --> 09:38.411
Matt,
we have a possible RMR.

09:38.411 --> 09:39.829
We need to mobilize
every resource

09:39.829 --> 09:41.623
to evacuate
the Angeles Forest.

09:41.623 --> 09:43.374
We're heading back
to locate the source.

09:43.374 --> 09:44.626
We?

09:44.626 --> 09:47.462
As in...you and me?

09:47.462 --> 09:49.255
[ Geiger counter clicking ]

09:52.592 --> 09:56.805
Thanks again for making me work
the nuclear jungle beat.

09:56.805 --> 09:58.723
Could this get
any worse?

09:58.723 --> 10:01.142
[ Geiger counter clicking
rapidly ]
Apparently, yes.

10:01.142 --> 10:11.069
♪♪

10:11.069 --> 10:13.404
Even in these suits, we
should only stay for a minute.

10:13.404 --> 10:18.618
♪♪

10:18.618 --> 10:24.040
♪♪

10:24.040 --> 10:25.542
Carter.

10:27.252 --> 10:29.504
It's Wallace.

10:29.504 --> 10:32.674
He ran into something
way more dangerous than Bigfoot.

10:32.674 --> 10:34.676
Yeah. His killer in here
making a dirty bomb.

10:42.142 --> 10:44.060
I don't understand.

10:44.060 --> 10:46.271
How do you go from a missing
person case to a dirty bomb?

10:46.271 --> 10:47.856
And why were you investigating
it in the first place?

10:47.856 --> 10:49.274
Oh, I don't see
how that's important

10:49.274 --> 10:50.400
unless you already know
the answer

10:50.400 --> 10:51.985
and you're trying
to catch me in a lie.

10:51.985 --> 10:54.821
I swear, Matt, just when I made
peace with your unit's autonomy,

10:54.821 --> 10:56.990
I find out you've turned it
into a favor mill

10:56.990 --> 10:58.491
doing investigations
on request

10:58.491 --> 11:00.410
for a mysterious
D. C. power player.

11:00.410 --> 11:03.079
Okay, first, let's dial back
on the drama.

11:03.079 --> 11:05.081
We all take requests
from on high.

11:05.081 --> 11:06.791
Second, thank God I did.
Hm?

11:06.791 --> 11:08.251
Or we might be
standing in the middle

11:08.251 --> 11:09.878
of a radioactive cloud
right now

11:09.878 --> 11:11.337
wondering
what the hell happened.

11:11.337 --> 11:14.215
So you're not gonna tell me
who Smith is?

11:14.215 --> 11:16.092
Someone with a whole lot
of juice, Tracy.

11:16.092 --> 11:17.218
That's all I can say.

11:17.218 --> 11:19.179
You realize I outrank you,
right?

11:21.556 --> 11:24.434
At approximately
10:45 this morning,

11:24.434 --> 11:27.145
agents discovered
the body of Wallace Yamashiro

11:27.145 --> 11:29.022
in a makeshift bunker
in the Angeles Forest.

11:29.022 --> 11:30.607
It is our belief
that he was killed

11:30.607 --> 11:32.567
after he stumbled
across this bunker

11:32.567 --> 11:34.944
where a radiological dispersion
device was being built.

11:34.944 --> 11:37.572
Now, we've generated a short
list of most likely subjects,

11:37.572 --> 11:40.158
and agents are out there
looking for them right now.

11:40.158 --> 11:42.994
LAPD will be assisting us
on a joint task force.

11:42.994 --> 11:44.954
Sergeant Grey.
Thank you.

11:44.954 --> 11:46.164
I've already briefed
my department

11:46.164 --> 11:47.957
on all pertinent details,

11:47.957 --> 11:50.668
and our Hazmat Response Unit
is on standby.

11:50.668 --> 11:53.213
Obviously, a tight lid
is paramount in this situation

11:53.213 --> 11:54.756
so as not to create
unnecessary panic.

11:54.756 --> 11:56.716
This isn't our first rodeo,
ma'am.

11:56.716 --> 11:59.761
Is there any insight into the
size of the bomb that was built?

11:59.761 --> 12:01.596
Not at this point.

12:01.596 --> 12:03.473
We're still trying to trace
the materials used,

12:03.473 --> 12:05.558
but until shown otherwise,
we need to assume

12:05.558 --> 12:07.644
that this bomb is live
and in the city somewhere.

12:07.644 --> 12:09.729
Matt, what do we have
on the man in custody?

12:09.729 --> 12:13.691
Well, Marlin Jagger was
discovered a quarter of a mile

12:13.691 --> 12:16.236
from the bunker
with acute radiation syndrome.

12:16.236 --> 12:18.404
He was wearing
the victim's backpack.

12:18.404 --> 12:20.990
I have my doubts about Marlin
being our bomb maker.

12:20.990 --> 12:23.493
He has no background in science
or engineering,

12:23.493 --> 12:26.287
no political ideology
that would suggest motive.

12:26.287 --> 12:27.997
Based on
his social media profile,

12:27.997 --> 12:29.499
he's the laziest man
on the planet.

12:29.499 --> 12:30.917
What's Marlin got to say
for himself?

12:30.917 --> 12:32.710
Well, he just regained
consciousness.

12:32.710 --> 12:34.837
Agents Clark and Hope
are speaking to him right now.

12:34.837 --> 12:36.464
Tell us about the bomb.

12:36.464 --> 12:37.632
The what?

12:37.632 --> 12:39.592
Mr. Jagger, we don't
have time for this.

12:39.592 --> 12:41.678
You're suffering from
severe radiation poisoning.

12:41.678 --> 12:43.680
And you were wearing
the backpack of a murder victim

12:43.680 --> 12:46.266
found in a bunker filled
with bomb-making material.

12:46.266 --> 12:48.393
Wait, wait.
Wallace is dead?

12:48.393 --> 12:51.020
Well, I found his pack
off a trail near Angel Falls.

12:51.020 --> 12:53.064
I-I picked it up
to give it back to him.

12:53.064 --> 12:56.276
I don't know anything
about a bunker or a bomb.

12:56.276 --> 12:58.152
Simone:
We are not buying it, okay?

12:58.152 --> 13:00.113
You don't get this sick

13:00.113 --> 13:02.282
without being exposed
to radiation

13:02.282 --> 13:04.784
for a long period
of time.

13:04.784 --> 13:06.160
How do you
explain that?

13:06.160 --> 13:08.204
Well,
I live right there.

13:08.204 --> 13:09.998
Right where?
In the woods?

13:09.998 --> 13:12.375
Yeah.
I'm a boondocker.
A what now?

13:12.375 --> 13:14.627
A person is legally allowed
to camp on public land

13:14.627 --> 13:16.337
for 14 days at a time.

13:16.337 --> 13:17.964
So if you move sites
every two weeks,

13:17.964 --> 13:20.008
you can basically live
in the forest for free.

13:20.008 --> 13:23.386
Please. I-I didn't have anything
to do with this.

13:23.386 --> 13:24.929
I swear, man.

13:24.929 --> 13:27.724
Well, have you seen anything
suspicious out there lately?

13:27.724 --> 13:29.642
Besides Bigfoot?
Wait, you've seen Bigfoot?

13:29.642 --> 13:31.352
Okay, hold.

13:31.352 --> 13:34.689
That [chuckles] is a
conversation for another day.

13:34.689 --> 13:37.066
Unless Sasquatch is out there
making a dirty bomb.

13:39.235 --> 13:41.195
You know,
there is one guy I've seen

13:41.195 --> 13:43.656
always carrying stuff
into the woods.

13:43.656 --> 13:46.075
Uh...

13:46.075 --> 13:50.163
A white dude, maybe 50s.

13:50.163 --> 13:54.250
He always wears this dirty coat
with a fur collar.

13:54.250 --> 13:55.752
Did you get a name?
Possible vehicle?

13:55.752 --> 13:57.295
Anything more
you can tell us?

13:57.295 --> 13:59.380
No, I...

13:59.380 --> 14:02.008
Oh, God,
I don't feel good.

14:02.008 --> 14:04.510
[ Monitor beeping ]

14:04.510 --> 14:06.179
Am I gonna die?

14:08.639 --> 14:11.976
We'll get someone to come
help you with the pain.

14:11.976 --> 14:14.145
Hang in there.

14:14.145 --> 14:15.480
That doesn't give us
much to go on.

14:15.480 --> 14:16.647
Ugh,
less than nothing.

14:16.647 --> 14:19.108
A mysterious old white man
in a nasty jacket.

14:19.108 --> 14:21.152
No way we can get an ID
off that.

14:21.152 --> 14:23.446
Sorry your birthday was ruined
by a mad bomber.

14:23.446 --> 14:25.656
Well, every bad day
is someone's birthday.

14:25.656 --> 14:28.242
Wow.
That's...dark.

14:28.242 --> 14:29.827
I am still gonna get you
a perfect gift, by the way.

14:29.827 --> 14:30.995
Mm.
Just putting it
out there.

14:30.995 --> 14:31.996
So I'm not getting
the pen.

14:31.996 --> 14:33.623
No.
Tell me something.
Okay.

14:33.623 --> 14:36.876
What's your, like,
dream vacation?

14:36.876 --> 14:39.879
Hmm. And by answering this,
you come up with a perfect gift?

14:39.879 --> 14:40.963
Mm-hmm.

14:40.963 --> 14:43.216
Hmm. Peru.

14:43.216 --> 14:44.634
I've always wanted to hike
Machu Picchu.

14:44.634 --> 14:45.635
Why haven't you?

14:45.635 --> 14:46.969
Too busy.

14:46.969 --> 14:48.179
Now go light a fire
under your BFF.

14:48.179 --> 14:49.639
We need
those test results.

14:49.639 --> 14:50.640
Not gonna help.

14:50.640 --> 14:52.266
I said something stupid,
screwed up.

14:52.266 --> 14:53.643
Then unscrew it up.

14:55.103 --> 14:57.188
[ Sighs ]

14:58.606 --> 15:01.317
Hey.

15:01.317 --> 15:04.987
The fur was synthetic,
so probably not Bigfoot.

15:04.987 --> 15:07.740
Oh, that -- that's actually
not why I'm here.

15:07.740 --> 15:11.035
Um, any luck
ID'ing the bomber?

15:11.035 --> 15:12.912
Latent prints have been scanned
into AFIS.

15:12.912 --> 15:14.413
We're running rapid DNA,

15:14.413 --> 15:16.082
but the radiation
makes it more complicated.

15:17.917 --> 15:19.752
I-I owe you an apology.

15:19.752 --> 15:22.922
Um, re-gifting that bottle
of wine was, uh --

15:22.922 --> 15:25.383
Tacky?
Rude? Gauche?

15:25.383 --> 15:29.137
I could give more adjectives
if you'd like.

15:29.137 --> 15:30.596
You should have
just lied to me.

15:30.596 --> 15:32.431
I-I kinda did.

15:32.431 --> 15:36.310
Um, but you see, t-the reason
I didn't tell you the truth --

15:36.310 --> 15:38.104
[ Computer beeps ]

15:40.523 --> 15:42.942
AFIS got a match to prints found
in the bunker.

15:45.361 --> 15:48.739
Orson Mettle,
a prolific eco-terrorist

15:48.739 --> 15:51.409
responsible for three
prior bombings in the U. S.

15:51.409 --> 15:55.204
A ski resort in Colorado
in protest of deforestation,

15:55.204 --> 15:56.831
a logging company
in Minnesota,

15:56.831 --> 15:59.292
and the last attack
occurred in Texas at the home

15:59.292 --> 16:02.420
of the CEO of a company
that genetically modifies food.

16:02.420 --> 16:05.089
Now, that bomb killed
his whole family.

16:05.089 --> 16:06.632
Any motive
behind his attacks?

16:06.632 --> 16:08.426
He published a manifesto
for each

16:08.426 --> 16:10.595
decrying humanity's effect
on Mother Earth.

16:10.595 --> 16:12.138
This many bombings --

16:12.138 --> 16:13.848
how's he managed
to stay out of handcuffs?

16:13.848 --> 16:15.224
Well,
he's a true loner.

16:15.224 --> 16:17.101
Lives completely
off the grid

16:17.101 --> 16:19.270
and just keeps his head down,
making bombs.

16:19.270 --> 16:21.272
Never used radiation
before.

16:21.272 --> 16:22.857
Garza: No. It's an escalation,
a break in the pattern,

16:22.857 --> 16:24.859
which is why he didn't show up
on our short list.

16:24.859 --> 16:26.360
Please tell me
you have a clue

16:26.360 --> 16:28.279
on how to find this guy
before it's too late.

16:28.279 --> 16:30.448
We do. His son, Tad,
he lives in Echo Park.

16:30.448 --> 16:32.241
[ Knock on door ]

16:33.701 --> 16:35.995
FBI. Special Agents Hope
and Clark.

16:35.995 --> 16:37.622
What'd Dad do
this time?

16:41.042 --> 16:44.045
I'm not at liberty
to say.

16:44.045 --> 16:46.464
You don't seem surprised
to see us.

16:46.464 --> 16:49.217
Feds, journalists, podcasters,
psycho groupies.

16:49.217 --> 16:50.343
Every time
my doorbell rings,

16:50.343 --> 16:52.136
I'm reminded
I'm the son of a monster.

16:52.136 --> 16:53.763
That's gotta be rough,

16:53.763 --> 16:55.806
paying for the sins
of your father.

16:55.806 --> 16:57.683
I can only imagine

16:57.683 --> 17:00.311
what life is like
under that microscope.

17:00.311 --> 17:02.021
Has your father reached out
in any way?

17:02.021 --> 17:03.689
Call, texted, anything?

17:03.689 --> 17:08.444
I-I made it clear
that he never contact me again.

17:08.444 --> 17:10.363
But?

17:10.363 --> 17:13.366
'Cause I sense
there's a but coming, hmm?

17:15.451 --> 17:18.871
Talk to us, sweetie.
We can help you with this.

17:25.836 --> 17:28.005
[ Sniffles ] This was in
my mailbox this morning.

17:28.005 --> 17:29.674
Is that
from your father?

17:29.674 --> 17:31.384
Why didn't you
notify us?

17:31.384 --> 17:34.178
Because of this.
You two here.

17:34.178 --> 17:36.556
I just got my life back
after the last bombing.

17:36.556 --> 17:38.474
The second I saw this,
I threw it in the trash.

17:40.393 --> 17:42.395
There's no stamp.
Letter wasn't mailed.

17:42.395 --> 17:44.188
He dropped it off himself.

17:44.188 --> 17:47.608
I mean, are we gonna open this
with a robot arm or something?

17:47.608 --> 17:49.068
No time for that.

17:52.613 --> 17:55.616
"I know you hate me, but it
wasn't always bad between us.

17:55.616 --> 17:58.286
Remember our hikes
in Hampton Park when
you were young?

17:58.286 --> 18:00.746
Those days are gone,
ruined now by human greed,

18:00.746 --> 18:03.874
another soulless corporation
trading beauty for profit.

18:03.874 --> 18:06.085
Well, I'm leveling
the playing field,

18:06.085 --> 18:08.129
so consider this
my last parental act.

18:08.129 --> 18:09.797
A warning --

18:09.797 --> 18:12.300
return to nature
like I taught you.

18:12.300 --> 18:14.135
You can survive."

18:14.135 --> 18:15.845
H-He's targeting
Hampton Park.

18:15.845 --> 18:18.139
I mean, w-why would he say
"return to nature"

18:18.139 --> 18:19.974
if he's just gonna
destroy it?

18:19.974 --> 18:23.894
Because it's already
being destroyed.

18:23.894 --> 18:25.688
They're about to build
condos on it.

18:25.688 --> 18:28.774
That park's near downtown.
His device blows...

18:28.774 --> 18:32.653
The Santa Ana winds spread
radiation all over the city.

18:32.653 --> 18:35.740
♪♪

18:35.740 --> 18:38.492
[ Sirens wailing ]

18:38.492 --> 18:39.827
Simone: Really?

18:39.827 --> 18:41.954
You just gonna go back
to doing your son's homework

18:41.954 --> 18:44.290
when there's
a loose RDD out there?

18:44.290 --> 18:45.583
Don't you want to
pack up your family

18:45.583 --> 18:46.709
and get the hell
out of town?

18:46.709 --> 18:47.835
Absolutely not.

18:47.835 --> 18:49.629
Why?
Because rules.

18:49.629 --> 18:50.755
You know
we can't tell anyone

18:50.755 --> 18:52.256
about what's going down
or what we do.

18:52.256 --> 18:53.299
I know, Carter,
but the thing i--

18:53.299 --> 18:54.550
But -- But nothing.

18:54.550 --> 18:56.677
There are threats out there
every day, all the time.

18:56.677 --> 18:59.972
The only way to cope is to
keep living and solve the case.

18:59.972 --> 19:04.101
♪ Processed, purchased,
consumed ♪

19:04.101 --> 19:05.770
[ Sirens wailing ]

19:05.770 --> 19:08.606
LAPD Pilot: Attention.
This is the LAPD.

19:08.606 --> 19:11.442
Please evacuate the area
immediately.

19:11.442 --> 19:12.818
Clear the premises!

19:12.818 --> 19:15.613
[ Police radio chatter ]

19:15.613 --> 19:17.657
Brendon:
What are we looking for?

19:17.657 --> 19:20.326
An RDD could be as small as a
suitcase and as big as a truck.

19:20.326 --> 19:22.286
Anything could be
suspicious.

19:22.286 --> 19:23.829
Right this way.
Off the merry-go-round, please.

19:23.829 --> 19:26.332
We need you all to stop playing
and leave the park now.

19:26.332 --> 19:27.667
Ma'am,
no time for that.

19:27.667 --> 19:29.460
Just take your daughter
and go.

19:29.460 --> 19:30.961
Sir,
you need to evacuate.

19:33.005 --> 19:34.048
Sir.

19:37.051 --> 19:39.178
FBI!
Show us your hands!

19:41.097 --> 19:42.264
Don't move.

19:44.809 --> 19:47.144
Or what?

19:47.144 --> 19:49.897
You're gonna shoot me?

19:49.897 --> 19:51.482
What if you miss?

19:51.482 --> 19:53.317
A stray bullet,
and this baby goes up.

19:53.317 --> 19:56.654
I'm already a dead man.

19:56.654 --> 19:59.824
Nice to know I won't be
leaving this world alone.

19:59.824 --> 20:02.493
♪♪

20:06.956 --> 20:09.917
Sir, listen.

20:09.917 --> 20:11.544
Nobody needs to die
today.

20:11.544 --> 20:14.088
Yes, they do.

20:14.088 --> 20:18.008
A little shock is what it takes
to wake the world up.

20:18.008 --> 20:20.136
What I know about you,
Orson,

20:20.136 --> 20:22.263
is that you've been making bombs
a long time,

20:22.263 --> 20:24.140
and you still got
all your limbs.

20:24.140 --> 20:26.809
That means
you're a careful cat,

20:26.809 --> 20:30.938
so there's no way you would have
activated that bomb...

20:30.938 --> 20:33.107
before you moved it here.

20:33.107 --> 20:35.860
I'm not worried about it
going off on its own.

20:35.860 --> 20:38.612
But let me tell you what
you should be worried about.

20:38.612 --> 20:42.533
My man Carter here
is a first-class shot.

20:42.533 --> 20:45.161
I'm not concerned about him
accidentally hitting that bomb

20:45.161 --> 20:47.496
trying to shoot you.

20:47.496 --> 20:51.041
Do yourself a favor
and give yourself up.

20:52.418 --> 20:53.878
No!

20:53.878 --> 20:55.671
[ Taser crackles ]

20:56.547 --> 20:57.965
[ Grunts ]

20:59.884 --> 21:01.302
[ Handcuffs click ]
Back out of there, Brendon.

21:01.302 --> 21:02.094
He's radioactive.

21:06.724 --> 21:08.809
Brendon:
That's a big-ass bomb.

21:08.809 --> 21:10.436
And Simone's right.
It's not activated.

21:10.436 --> 21:12.271
Okay, get out of there.
Let the bomb squad deal with it.

21:12.271 --> 21:17.693
♪♪

21:17.693 --> 21:20.112
Okay, so the initial
visual examination

21:20.112 --> 21:22.531
confirms that bomb
was an RDD.

21:22.531 --> 21:26.202
Iridium-192 interspersed with
enough conventional explosives

21:26.202 --> 21:27.536
to rip a hole
in the development site

21:27.536 --> 21:28.954
and irradiate whatever's left.

21:28.954 --> 21:31.373
But we saved
the damn day.

21:31.373 --> 21:32.750
Not so fast, Simone.

21:32.750 --> 21:35.127
We don't celebrate until
we tie off every loose thread.

21:35.127 --> 21:36.629
And the last time I checked,

21:36.629 --> 21:39.215
there's no dirty bomb section
at the Home Depot.

21:39.215 --> 21:41.133
Good point.
So where is all this

21:41.133 --> 21:43.511
high-grade radioactive material
coming from?

21:43.511 --> 21:45.179
Riverside.

21:45.179 --> 21:47.264
The lab was able to trace
the iridium container

21:47.264 --> 21:48.641
that we pulled
from Orson's bunker

21:48.641 --> 21:49.892
to an industrial plant
there.

21:49.892 --> 21:51.602
The site manager
is on his way now.

21:51.602 --> 21:52.728
Okay, Carter, Simone,

21:52.728 --> 21:54.730
you meet with him
when he arrives.

21:54.730 --> 21:56.732
Let's find out if Orson has
an accomplice or not.

21:56.732 --> 21:59.026
We're on it.

22:01.570 --> 22:04.156
Hey, uh, I have
another question for you.

22:04.156 --> 22:06.033
It's about
your birthday gift.

22:06.033 --> 22:08.410
What's the weirdest dream
you've ever had?

22:08.410 --> 22:09.620
Really? Right now?

22:09.620 --> 22:11.205
Yeah.
Why not right now?

22:11.205 --> 22:12.581
Mm,
can I just have the pen?

22:12.581 --> 22:14.250
No.
I really like pens.

22:14.250 --> 22:17.127
No, no, no, no.
Weirdest dream. Just...go.

22:17.127 --> 22:19.171
Well, I would
write it down for you,

22:19.171 --> 22:20.756
but unfortunately,
I don't have a pen.

22:20.756 --> 22:22.508
Hint, hint.

22:22.508 --> 22:23.425
Okay, fine.

22:23.425 --> 22:25.553
Um...

22:25.553 --> 22:27.930
I was driving
really fast...
Mm-hmm.

22:27.930 --> 22:29.640
...on a highway
in the clouds.

22:29.640 --> 22:31.642
I was going
130 miles per hour.

22:31.642 --> 22:34.270
And then I looked down,
and I wasn't wearing a seatbelt.

22:34.270 --> 22:36.105
But instead
of being scared,

22:36.105 --> 22:39.859
I just closed my eyes
and I went faster.

22:39.859 --> 22:42.695
Based on that,
do you know what to get me?

22:42.695 --> 22:44.613
Not yet,
but I-I'm getting closer.

22:44.613 --> 22:46.448
Okay. That's nice.

22:46.448 --> 22:48.868
[ Cellphone vibrates, clicks ]

22:48.868 --> 22:50.327
Special Agent Clark.

22:50.327 --> 22:51.745
Yo, it's Greg.

22:51.745 --> 22:54.623
What? Are you calling
to ask me out on a date again?

22:54.623 --> 22:56.125
Ha! I need your help.

22:56.125 --> 22:57.877
It's about your father.

22:57.877 --> 22:59.628
One of his businesses
is in trouble.

22:59.628 --> 23:00.880
Brotherhood Bakery?

23:00.880 --> 23:02.715
Yeah, for the past
couple of months,

23:02.715 --> 23:05.175
it's been hemorrhaging cash
that I can't seem to trace.

23:05.175 --> 23:08.470
So I'm thinking that
this manager, ex-con named --

23:08.470 --> 23:10.848
Ah,
formerly incarcerated.

23:10.848 --> 23:12.141
Right. My bad.

23:12.141 --> 23:14.435
This formerly incarcerated man
named Darius

23:14.435 --> 23:15.644
might be stealing
from him.

23:15.644 --> 23:18.188
And I'm guessing
you're not talking scones.

23:18.188 --> 23:19.899
No.
I'm not talking scones.

23:19.899 --> 23:23.110
I'm talking a couple of
thousand dollars at this point,

23:23.110 --> 23:25.279
disappearing
right under Cutty's nose.

23:25.279 --> 23:27.448
And you told my dad
about this?

23:27.448 --> 23:30.534
I did.
And he shut me down, hard.

23:30.534 --> 23:33.037
So I'm thinking maybe
you can talk to him,

23:33.037 --> 23:35.331
see if he can look into this
before it gets any worse.

23:35.331 --> 23:37.333
Yeah, I will.

23:37.333 --> 23:39.209
Thanks for this.

23:39.209 --> 23:40.753
[ Cellphone beeps ]

23:40.753 --> 23:42.296
[ Ringing ]

23:42.296 --> 23:44.757
This is Cutty.
You know what to do.
[ Beep ]

23:44.757 --> 23:47.343
Daddy, you better not be
screening my calls.

23:47.343 --> 23:49.470
Greg told me
about the bakery situation.

23:49.470 --> 23:51.889
I need you to listen
and get it straight.

23:51.889 --> 23:54.058
You call me back as soon
as you get this,

23:54.058 --> 23:56.560
and I mean it, Cutty Clark.

23:56.560 --> 23:58.354
Don't you dare
go ghosting me.

23:59.605 --> 24:01.523
Eddie Mendoza?
Yes, sir.

24:01.523 --> 24:03.150
I'm Special Agent Hope.
This is Special Agent Clark.

24:03.150 --> 24:04.026
Thanks for coming down.

24:04.026 --> 24:06.111
Not a problem.
Have a seat.

24:06.111 --> 24:07.821
And I'm just relieved
that you recovered

24:07.821 --> 24:09.365
the radioactive material.

24:09.365 --> 24:11.408
It's just -- It's been
a nightmare since the burglary.

24:11.408 --> 24:12.952
What is
an industrial plant doing

24:12.952 --> 24:14.578
with iridium
laying around?

24:14.578 --> 24:17.081
We use it as part
of radiography equipment.

24:17.081 --> 24:19.708
It helps detect cracks
or defects in metal pipes.

24:19.708 --> 24:21.460
Now, our security
is top-notch,

24:21.460 --> 24:23.629
but I went in there last month
and someone had broke in.

24:23.629 --> 24:27.549
They stole 720 Ci's worth
of iridium-192 pellets.

24:27.549 --> 24:29.259
Hold on.

24:29.259 --> 24:34.181
The prelim report said our
subject's RDD only had 350 Ci's.

24:34.181 --> 24:36.225
He only used half
of what he stole.

24:36.225 --> 24:39.019
Orson built
a second bomb.

24:39.019 --> 24:41.063
SAC Chiles:
Where is it?

24:41.063 --> 24:44.942
Orson: You're going to have
to be more specific than that.

24:44.942 --> 24:46.944
We know you had enough
radioactive material

24:46.944 --> 24:48.570
to make two dirty bombs.

24:48.570 --> 24:50.072
Which means you must have
planted the first one

24:50.072 --> 24:51.740
before we found you.

24:51.740 --> 24:53.283
Where's the other one?

24:53.283 --> 24:57.204
Oh, that.
Well, it's in a special place.

24:57.204 --> 25:01.250
Our techs say the RDD you made
was pretty damn impressive.

25:01.250 --> 25:02.710
Well, thank you.

25:02.710 --> 25:05.212
I do take pride in my work,
so...

25:05.212 --> 25:07.089
We assume you activated
the first bomb

25:07.089 --> 25:09.091
and got caught
before you could arm the second.

25:09.091 --> 25:11.010
Assume away.

25:11.010 --> 25:13.012
The bomb
we caught you with

25:13.012 --> 25:15.055
had a three-hour timer
on it,

25:15.055 --> 25:16.265
and that was
about an hour ago.

25:16.265 --> 25:20.144
Which means you have
less than two hours before

25:20.144 --> 25:21.854
[imitates explosion]

25:21.854 --> 25:24.732
Okay, listen, Orson,

25:24.732 --> 25:27.359
it's not too late for you
to do the right thing here.

25:27.359 --> 25:29.236
I'm done talking.

25:29.236 --> 25:31.947
[ Monitor beeping ]

25:31.947 --> 25:33.741
Tick.

25:33.741 --> 25:35.576
Tick.

25:35.576 --> 25:37.453
Tick.

25:37.453 --> 25:39.455
Tick.

25:39.455 --> 25:40.080
Tick.

25:44.126 --> 25:46.545
Garza:
The SAC and I struck out.

25:46.545 --> 25:49.214
Orson's not giving up
the location of his second bomb.

25:49.214 --> 25:51.008
Give me a chance
to talk to him, sir.

25:51.008 --> 25:53.260
The man's last dying wish is
to irradiate the city, Simone.

25:53.260 --> 25:55.262
What makes you think he's gonna
want to talk to you?

25:55.262 --> 25:57.806
Not just me,
but me and his son.

25:57.806 --> 26:00.684
I feel like we really connected
when we went by his house.

26:00.684 --> 26:03.479
Orson warned him
about the RDD.

26:03.479 --> 26:05.397
He might want
to kill Los Angeles,

26:05.397 --> 26:07.399
but not everybody
in it.

26:07.399 --> 26:08.609
She has a point.

26:08.609 --> 26:10.402
There's some semblance
of humanity left in him.

26:10.402 --> 26:11.653
Maybe the son
can help her find it.

26:11.653 --> 26:13.155
Let's try it.

26:13.155 --> 26:14.698
I'm on it.

26:15.908 --> 26:18.160
[ Sirens wailing ]

26:19.286 --> 26:20.913
Why did you
bring him here?

26:20.913 --> 26:23.874
I asked, and he came.

26:23.874 --> 26:26.502
You look good.

26:26.502 --> 26:28.712
You don't.

26:28.712 --> 26:31.381
You still have time
to run.

26:31.381 --> 26:33.634
And you still have time
to stop this.

26:33.634 --> 26:35.052
Think --
Think about your son.

26:35.052 --> 26:37.179
Think about
all the innocent people.

26:37.179 --> 26:38.931
There are no innocents.

26:38.931 --> 26:42.351
We all have to pay for what
we've done to the Earth.

26:42.351 --> 26:44.144
Even your boy?

26:48.023 --> 26:51.318
The world shrugged off
the science.

26:51.318 --> 26:54.947
Well, no one can ignore
what I will unleash.

26:54.947 --> 26:59.034
The skies will burn
and the sun will be darkened.

26:59.034 --> 27:00.953
Okay, now you just cribbin'
from the Book of Revelation.

27:00.953 --> 27:03.872
Dad, stop this.

27:03.872 --> 27:05.916
[ Monitor beeping ]

27:07.793 --> 27:10.254
No.

27:10.254 --> 27:13.715
Okay, so Orson said
the skies will burn

27:13.715 --> 27:15.217
and the sun
will be darkened.

27:15.217 --> 27:17.219
In all of his
previous manifestos,

27:17.219 --> 27:19.054
he's never used language
like that.

27:19.054 --> 27:21.265
So you think that's a clue
as to where the second bomb is?

27:21.265 --> 27:23.183
Maybe.
I don't know.

27:23.183 --> 27:25.811
Well, let's think about it.
Skies will burn.

27:25.811 --> 27:26.812
How would one do that?

27:26.812 --> 27:28.564
Start a huge fire,

27:28.564 --> 27:30.774
one that's damn near impossible
to put out.

27:30.774 --> 27:33.819
Yeah, like a forest fire
or -- or an oil refinery.

27:33.819 --> 27:37.906
No, no, no.
An oil well.

27:37.906 --> 27:41.702
There are thousands of active
oil wells in Los Angeles

27:41.702 --> 27:44.079
drilling for oil
underneath the city.

27:44.079 --> 27:46.456
I mean, we got them
all over my neighborhood.

27:46.456 --> 27:48.292
Yeah, you put a bomb
in one of those, boom!

27:48.292 --> 27:50.627
And he said,
"The sun will be darkened."

27:50.627 --> 27:53.130
Setting off an RDD
at an oil field would ignite

27:53.130 --> 27:55.299
a never-ending
radioactive fire,

27:55.299 --> 27:56.925
one that would kill
almost every firefighter

27:56.925 --> 27:57.926
that tried to put it out.

27:57.926 --> 27:59.428
So then that's it.

27:59.428 --> 28:00.888
We got to warn people
and evacuate the city.

28:00.888 --> 28:02.931
We can't.
Why?

28:02.931 --> 28:04.808
4 million panicked people
will only make things worse.

28:04.808 --> 28:06.310
She's right, Simone.

28:06.310 --> 28:07.936
The way we help people
is by doing our jobs.

28:07.936 --> 28:10.939
And right now, that means
pinpointing the exact location.

28:10.939 --> 28:12.357
When the Super Bowl
came to L. A.,

28:12.357 --> 28:15.068
the NNSA had helicopters
with radiation sensors monitor

28:15.068 --> 28:17.321
for increased levels
of radiation.

28:17.321 --> 28:19.698
Okay, well, I'll make
some phone calls and
scramble the airships,

28:19.698 --> 28:22.159
but right now, we
need to hit all the
major oil fields first,

28:22.159 --> 28:23.744
so let's move.

28:23.744 --> 28:25.537
[ Indistinct conversations ]

28:27.122 --> 28:29.875
Where are you going?
To be with my team.

28:29.875 --> 28:32.669
Well, this is your task force,
Matt. Your job is here.

28:32.669 --> 28:35.756
Command and control.
You hand-picked this team.

28:35.756 --> 28:36.924
Now you have to
trust them.

28:38.300 --> 28:40.052
Carter:
Pull our Bu-car around front.

28:40.052 --> 28:41.887
I've got to coordinate
with Smith and Dawes.

28:41.887 --> 28:45.724
[ FaceTime rings, clicks ]

28:45.724 --> 28:47.142
Hey, Daddy.

28:47.142 --> 28:49.853
Simone, I got your rude
voicemail.

28:49.853 --> 28:51.772
Hear me out, okay?

28:51.772 --> 28:54.316
Greg thinks Darius
is skimming from you.

28:54.316 --> 28:56.026
Yeah, he is.

28:56.026 --> 28:57.861
Wait. You knew?

28:57.861 --> 29:01.114
Look, I've known Darius
forever.

29:01.114 --> 29:03.659
He's got heart,
but he's proud.

29:03.659 --> 29:06.328
And he's ashamed
of his faults.

29:06.328 --> 29:09.623
But if he's stealing money,
it's for a good reason.

29:09.623 --> 29:11.917
You can't let people like that
take advantage of you.

29:11.917 --> 29:13.377
If you do,
you'll end up broke.

29:13.377 --> 29:15.045
I'm just looking out,
and I --

29:15.045 --> 29:17.756
No, I-I don't need anyone
looking out.

29:17.756 --> 29:21.635
What I need is for you
to mind your own damn business.

29:21.635 --> 29:23.345
Daddy, please.

29:23.345 --> 29:25.013
At least tell Greg what's up.

29:25.013 --> 29:26.640
He's as concerned as I am.

29:26.640 --> 29:27.724
Like I care.

29:27.724 --> 29:30.644
He crosses this line again,
he is fired.

29:30.644 --> 29:32.396
And don't even
think about involving

29:32.396 --> 29:34.231
your little LAPD buddies
in this.

29:34.231 --> 29:36.566
I'm handling this
my own way.

29:38.652 --> 29:41.154
What -- What --
What's the matter?

29:42.698 --> 29:44.449
I love you, Daddy.

29:44.449 --> 29:47.703
No, no, I-I love you,
too, baby girl.

29:49.538 --> 29:51.498
Simone,
what's going on?

29:53.542 --> 29:55.502
Daddy, listen.

29:55.502 --> 29:58.213
Hey,
I am dead serious.

29:58.213 --> 30:01.049
I need you to get out
of the city right now.

30:01.049 --> 30:02.342
Why?

30:02.342 --> 30:04.386
Mr. Clarke,
Simone has to go now.

30:04.386 --> 30:05.887
[ FaceTime ends ]

30:05.887 --> 30:11.476
♪♪

30:15.939 --> 30:18.775
I could fire you right now.
But you know that, don't you?

30:18.775 --> 30:21.695
FBI agents are prohibited
from warning citizens

30:21.695 --> 30:25.407
of possible threats before
that information is made public.

30:25.407 --> 30:30.245
I know the rules, Carter,
but a dirty bomb in South L. A.

30:30.245 --> 30:32.497
could detonate right
in my father's backyard.

30:32.497 --> 30:34.750
I couldn't live with myself
if he got hurt.

30:34.750 --> 30:37.085
Find a way.

30:37.085 --> 30:38.670
Wow.

30:38.670 --> 30:40.338
I don't get you.

30:40.338 --> 30:43.884
I mean, you could whittle away
all day at a car for your son,

30:43.884 --> 30:46.136
but won't do anything
to save his life?

30:46.136 --> 30:48.388
What the hell do you think
I've been doing?

30:48.388 --> 30:50.140
Helping to find this bomb
before it goes off

30:50.140 --> 30:51.767
is saving my son's life.

30:51.767 --> 30:53.518
And anyone else's sons,
too.

30:53.518 --> 30:55.270
And their daughters
and their mothers

30:55.270 --> 30:57.355
and their fathers,
including yours.

30:57.355 --> 30:58.690
I'm sorry.

30:58.690 --> 31:00.484
Yes, you are.

31:00.484 --> 31:02.235
But no one's got time
for that right now.

31:02.235 --> 31:04.112
You swore to do a job.

31:04.112 --> 31:05.363
Now can you do it,
or not?

31:06.782 --> 31:08.033
Yes, sir.

31:08.033 --> 31:11.036
[ Police radio chatter ]

31:11.036 --> 31:14.790
No sign of increased radiation
over the West Side.

31:14.790 --> 31:16.625
Man: That's a negative
in San Gabriel Valley.

31:16.625 --> 31:18.126
Come on. Come on.

31:20.170 --> 31:22.005
Wait.
I've got something.

31:22.005 --> 31:24.382
Abnormal levels of radiation
have been detected

31:24.382 --> 31:26.760
over the oil fields
east of downtown.

31:26.760 --> 31:29.304
That's a huge repository.
If an RDD goes off there...

31:31.848 --> 31:33.725
I'll notify the team.

31:33.725 --> 31:35.477
[ Sirens wailing ]

31:35.477 --> 31:45.112
♪♪

31:45.112 --> 31:54.746
♪♪

31:54.746 --> 31:56.665
Spread out
into teams of two.

31:56.665 --> 31:59.334
Use your Geiger counters
to track the radiation.

31:59.334 --> 32:00.585
Let's go!

32:00.585 --> 32:06.466
♪♪

32:06.466 --> 32:12.055
♪♪

32:12.055 --> 32:14.141
One last question.

32:14.141 --> 32:15.725
You cannot be serious
right now.

32:15.725 --> 32:17.018
[ Geiger counters clicking ]
What was
the first poster

32:17.018 --> 32:19.604
that you had on your wall
when you were a kid?

32:19.604 --> 32:22.357
Really?
Yeah. Do me a favor.
Humor me.

32:22.357 --> 32:24.943
Um, Jonas Salk.

32:24.943 --> 32:26.486
What?

32:26.486 --> 32:27.988
Jonas Salk.

32:27.988 --> 32:29.865
The guy who invented
the polio vaccine

32:29.865 --> 32:31.283
was your childhood crush?

32:31.283 --> 32:32.617
Well, no,
he wasn't a crush.

32:32.617 --> 32:34.536
Although
in his college photos,

32:34.536 --> 32:36.997
he did have this sort of hot,
nerdy thing going on.

32:36.997 --> 32:39.416
But how does this help you
figure out what to get me?

32:39.416 --> 32:41.001
Y-You know what?
Don't answer that.

32:41.001 --> 32:42.627
A bomb could go off
any second.

32:42.627 --> 32:45.755
So let's just focus
on the crisis at hand, please.

32:45.755 --> 32:48.717
[ Geiger counters clicking ]
Carter:
It's got to be nearby.

32:48.717 --> 32:50.677
[ Geiger counters clicking
rapidly ]

32:50.677 --> 32:52.053
It's picking up.

32:54.556 --> 32:56.057
Carter, there it is!

32:56.057 --> 32:57.851
We found the bomb!

32:57.851 --> 32:59.102
By the refinery tanks!

32:59.102 --> 33:01.062
[ Clicking stops ]

33:02.731 --> 33:04.441
The bomb tech team's
heading your way,

33:04.441 --> 33:06.067
but they're coming
from the other end of the field.

33:06.067 --> 33:08.028
No, no, no. There's less than
two minutes left on the clock.

33:08.028 --> 33:09.529
They're not gonna
make it here in time.

33:09.529 --> 33:11.198
Then you're gonna have
to defuse the bomb yourselves.

33:11.198 --> 33:12.908
We're gonna have to
do what now?

33:12.908 --> 33:15.327
We have a copy of Orson's bomb
schematics from the bunker.

33:15.327 --> 33:16.203
We can
walk you through it.

33:17.287 --> 33:19.039
We don't have any tools.

33:19.039 --> 33:20.081
Speak for yourself.

33:22.209 --> 33:23.919
Alright,
where do we start?

33:23.919 --> 33:25.253
Less than a minute.

33:25.253 --> 33:27.422
Yeah, I know.
Just give me a second.

33:27.422 --> 33:29.257
Seconds is
what we don't have.

33:29.257 --> 33:30.926
I understand, Simone.

33:30.926 --> 33:32.636
Okay,
by the looks of this,

33:32.636 --> 33:35.138
the green wire connects
the detonator to the timer.

33:35.138 --> 33:38.183
So if you cut that,
the timer turns off.

33:38.183 --> 33:39.184
I hope.

33:39.184 --> 33:42.270
You hope?
Wait, you said green.

33:42.270 --> 33:44.689
T-T-There are only red wires
in here.

33:44.689 --> 33:46.775
I think the middle one is going
to the detonator, though.

33:46.775 --> 33:48.193
Are you sure?
No!

33:48.193 --> 33:50.362
But if you have
any better ideas...

33:50.362 --> 33:51.696
I'm cutting the wire now.

33:51.696 --> 33:55.408
♪♪

33:55.408 --> 33:57.410
I can't reach it. My hands
are too big to fit in there.

33:57.410 --> 33:58.411
Simone,
you got to do this.

33:58.411 --> 33:59.829
Me?
Yes.

33:59.829 --> 34:01.164
You can do this, Simone.

34:01.164 --> 34:03.166
[ Timer beeping ]

34:03.166 --> 34:11.508
♪♪

34:11.508 --> 34:13.218
[ Beeping stops ]

34:13.218 --> 34:15.387
She did it.
She did it.

34:15.387 --> 34:17.097
[ Cheering ]

34:17.097 --> 34:20.058
Thank you.
Thank you.

34:20.058 --> 34:22.727
Good job.

34:22.727 --> 34:24.521
[ Breathing heavily ]

34:26.690 --> 34:29.484
Man: Threat contained.
Securing the site now.

34:29.484 --> 34:32.445
♪♪

34:32.445 --> 34:34.489
Mm.

34:38.743 --> 34:41.538
Carter:
You did good work today.

34:43.164 --> 34:45.458
But also screwed up
royally.

34:45.458 --> 34:46.918
I know.

34:46.918 --> 34:49.212
I'm sorry
about warning my dad.

34:50.839 --> 34:53.258
You gonna fire me?

34:53.258 --> 34:55.302
Not this time.

34:55.302 --> 34:58.221
But we follow strict protocols
for a reason.

34:58.221 --> 35:00.015
It can never happen again.
Hear me?

35:00.015 --> 35:01.558
Loud and clear.

35:01.558 --> 35:03.143
Go home.

35:03.143 --> 35:04.394
Before I change my mind.

35:04.394 --> 35:06.688
[ L. J. Waiters' "Natural Baby"
plays ]

35:06.688 --> 35:08.690
[ Exhales slowly ]

35:08.690 --> 35:13.028
♪♪

35:13.028 --> 35:15.739
Who would have thought that
my little missing persons case

35:15.739 --> 35:18.408
would lead us to apprehending
an eco-terrorist, huh?

35:18.408 --> 35:21.077
I'm sure you'll get
another commendation.

35:21.077 --> 35:22.912
Listen,
you were right.

35:22.912 --> 35:24.831
I usually am.

35:24.831 --> 35:27.709
But what specifically
were you referring to?

35:27.709 --> 35:31.671
Hanging back,
supervising my team from afar.

35:31.671 --> 35:34.007
Yeah, it takes
some getting used to.

35:34.007 --> 35:36.593
At least...
for me, it did.

35:36.593 --> 35:38.178
Yeah.

35:38.178 --> 35:40.305
We worked well together
today.

35:40.305 --> 35:42.807
Yeah, we really did.

35:42.807 --> 35:46.519
♪ She doesn't try to be
anything she ain't ♪

35:46.519 --> 35:49.814
Look, Matt, I know
I'm the big bad wolf here,

35:49.814 --> 35:52.984
but you using your friendship
with whomever Senator Smith is

35:52.984 --> 35:55.445
to cut corners
is dangerous.

35:55.445 --> 35:57.322
Actually,
I'm fine with it.

35:57.322 --> 36:00.241
♪ I'm talking 'bout
her beauty ♪

36:00.241 --> 36:01.993
Yeah, that right there's
the problem.

36:01.993 --> 36:03.536
♪ My babe's a natural beauty ♪

36:03.536 --> 36:06.748
Tracy,
we saved Los Angeles today.

36:06.748 --> 36:10.168
Why can't
we just enjoy that?

36:10.168 --> 36:11.795
For right now.

36:11.795 --> 36:14.589
♪♪

36:14.589 --> 36:16.424
There's no alcohol
allowed.

36:16.424 --> 36:20.345
♪ That every fella
just loves to touch ♪

36:20.345 --> 36:22.389
Yeah,
pour me a double.

36:22.389 --> 36:24.140
♪♪

36:24.140 --> 36:26.976
♪ And her smile so sweet ♪

36:26.976 --> 36:28.520
♪ Ooh ♪

36:28.520 --> 36:33.400
♪ Lord, it's much, much,
too much ♪

36:33.400 --> 36:36.778
Hey, uh, thank you
for your help earlier.

36:36.778 --> 36:38.738
It's what I'm paid
to do.

36:38.738 --> 36:40.073
Yeah, no, I know.

36:40.073 --> 36:42.075
Um...

36:42.075 --> 36:44.285
So, uh, we -- we got interrupted
earlier

36:44.285 --> 36:46.746
when we were talking
about the wine.

36:46.746 --> 36:47.789
It doesn't matter.

36:47.789 --> 36:50.375
No, it --
it does, actually.

36:50.375 --> 36:53.628
The reason I-I haven't...

36:53.628 --> 36:57.465
opened the bottle
is because I'm...

36:57.465 --> 36:59.843
sober.

36:59.843 --> 37:04.139
247 days.

37:04.139 --> 37:05.890
I had no idea.
No, no, no.

37:05.890 --> 37:08.560
There's -- There's -- There's
no reason for you to have.

37:08.560 --> 37:12.355
I-I-I don't really...
talk about it a lot,

37:12.355 --> 37:16.359
but, um, you know,
I hurt a lot of people

37:16.359 --> 37:18.570
and -- and made
a lot of mistakes.

37:18.570 --> 37:20.363
So...

37:20.363 --> 37:23.867
Not for
the past 247 days.

37:23.867 --> 37:27.787
[ Chuckles ]
That takes
a lot of courage.

37:27.787 --> 37:30.832
Thank you for
sharing that with me.

37:30.832 --> 37:31.958
Sure.

37:31.958 --> 37:35.086
Do you drink coffee?

37:35.086 --> 37:37.672
That's like asking me
if I breathe air.

37:37.672 --> 37:40.175
Tomorrow,
we should grab a cup.

37:40.175 --> 37:41.593
Okay.

37:41.593 --> 37:44.095
It's a date.

37:44.095 --> 37:47.265
No, it's coffee.

37:47.265 --> 37:49.184
You'll know
when we're going on a date.

37:50.769 --> 37:53.146
[ Conversing in French ]

37:57.817 --> 38:00.695
[ L. J. Waiters' "Baby
Who's Been Foolin' You" plays ]

38:00.695 --> 38:02.363
♪ Baby ♪

38:02.363 --> 38:04.073
Oh, hello, there.

38:04.073 --> 38:05.074
Hey, Simone.

38:05.074 --> 38:06.785
♪ Who's been fooling you ♪

38:06.785 --> 38:07.660
♪ I just wanna know now ♪

38:07.660 --> 38:08.995
No, we're good.

38:08.995 --> 38:10.205
And thanks
for your help.

38:10.205 --> 38:12.582
Thanks for looking out
for him.

38:12.582 --> 38:14.751
My pleasure.

38:14.751 --> 38:18.713
Who knew you'd turn out to be
a decent human being,

38:18.713 --> 38:22.175
after I watched you cheat on
all those tests in high school?

38:22.175 --> 38:23.676
You know, if that helps
you sleep at night, Simone,

38:23.676 --> 38:25.303
you can have it.

38:25.303 --> 38:27.639
But it's good to know
you were looking.

38:27.639 --> 38:29.432
Please. You know
you were checking me out.

38:29.432 --> 38:31.351
You were always thirsty
in high school.

38:31.351 --> 38:32.393
I was checking
you out?

38:32.393 --> 38:34.187
Ple-- Uh, yes.

38:34.187 --> 38:36.856
Either way, thank you.

38:36.856 --> 38:39.609
I will never forget
what you did for him.

38:40.985 --> 38:42.320
Don't mention it.

38:42.320 --> 38:44.447
♪ Baby, what in the world
came over you? ♪

38:44.447 --> 38:46.491
♪ I just gotta know now ♪

38:46.491 --> 38:47.784
[ Door closes ]

38:47.784 --> 38:52.372
♪ You don't believe
that the ocean is blue ♪

38:52.372 --> 38:57.168
I can be stubborn
sometimes.

38:57.168 --> 39:01.589
And I am
my father's daughter.

39:01.589 --> 39:03.341
Tell me what happened.

39:03.341 --> 39:06.427
Well,
I talked to Darius.

39:06.427 --> 39:09.556
He needed money
for his aunt's insulin.

39:09.556 --> 39:11.766
Didn't know
who to turn to.

39:11.766 --> 39:13.977
I mean,
he felt horrible.

39:13.977 --> 39:16.563
And he insisted
on working out a plan

39:16.563 --> 39:18.147
to pay back the money.

39:18.147 --> 39:20.275
♪ Your confidence
will set you free ♪

39:20.275 --> 39:23.987
He made a mistake.
And he's sorry.

39:23.987 --> 39:28.032
No one needs to go to jail,
and no one needs to get fired.

39:28.032 --> 39:29.450
♪ Are you gonna
let me love you? ♪

39:29.450 --> 39:32.579
You are a good man,
Cutty Clark.

39:32.579 --> 39:35.582
You scared me
pretty good

39:35.582 --> 39:38.251
on that phone call
earlier.

39:38.251 --> 39:40.587
Had me packing my bags
and everything.

39:40.587 --> 39:43.715
I'm sorry, Daddy.

39:43.715 --> 39:46.885
But I can't
really talk about it.

39:46.885 --> 39:49.512
And I hope
you understand.

39:49.512 --> 39:51.472
I do.

39:51.472 --> 39:52.557
♪ Tell me
who been foolin' you ♪

39:52.557 --> 39:54.976
[ Chuckles ]

39:54.976 --> 39:58.521
My baby girl
saving the world.

39:58.521 --> 40:01.482
[ Both laugh ]

40:01.482 --> 40:02.609
Something like that.

40:02.609 --> 40:03.735
Mm.

40:03.735 --> 40:05.695
Mm.

40:05.695 --> 40:08.281
♪ I really want to know now ♪

40:08.281 --> 40:10.450
♪ Good God almighty, baby ♪

40:10.450 --> 40:12.911
♪ Oh, now tell me who been
foolin' you? ♪

40:12.911 --> 40:14.579
♪ Hey, hey, yeah ♪

40:14.579 --> 40:16.122
All done?

40:16.122 --> 40:18.458
Behold, the Hopemobile.

40:18.458 --> 40:19.751
Mm.

40:19.751 --> 40:22.337
Hey. Whoa.
You're here early.

40:22.337 --> 40:26.049
Yeah, well, I wanted
to give you this.

40:26.049 --> 40:27.258
Ah.

40:27.258 --> 40:28.426
I know your birthday
was yesterday,

40:28.426 --> 40:32.013
but as promised,
the perfect gift.

40:32.013 --> 40:34.015
Yeah, right.
Based on those three questions?

40:34.015 --> 40:35.725
There's no way
that gave you anything.

40:35.725 --> 40:38.645
Oh, no, no, no, no.
They told me everything.

40:38.645 --> 40:40.021
You wanted to hike
Machu Picchu,

40:40.021 --> 40:41.397
but you never pulled
the trigger.

40:41.397 --> 40:43.399
You had a dream where you were
driving without a seatbelt,

40:43.399 --> 40:44.651
and it just made
you go even faster.

40:44.651 --> 40:46.194
You crave adventure
in your mind,

40:46.194 --> 40:48.071
but you're too sensible
in reality

40:48.071 --> 40:50.073
to actually
go through with it.

40:50.073 --> 40:54.744
Wow. That's...not at all
on the mark.

40:54.744 --> 40:56.162
Damn it.

40:56.162 --> 40:57.956
Well, what about
the Jonas Salk poster?

40:57.956 --> 40:59.749
Oh, you're also
very weird.

40:59.749 --> 41:01.709
Happy birthday.

41:01.709 --> 41:03.962
[ Chuckles ]

41:03.962 --> 41:05.630
Hmm.
Gift certificate?

41:05.630 --> 41:08.132
Skydiving?

41:08.132 --> 41:09.300
That sounds terrifying.

41:09.300 --> 41:11.469
It is. That's why
I'm going with you.

41:11.469 --> 41:14.681
Really? I've always wanted
to do this.

41:14.681 --> 41:16.599
Oh. So much better
than a pen.

41:16.599 --> 41:18.142
Thank you.

41:18.142 --> 41:21.688
Well, you'll need one of these
to sign the waiver.

41:23.022 --> 41:24.899
Everyone in
the briefing room now.

41:24.899 --> 41:29.487
♪♪

41:29.487 --> 41:30.863
Sorry, boss.

41:32.699 --> 41:33.574
What'd I miss?

41:33.574 --> 41:35.118
You're just in time.

41:35.118 --> 41:37.704
The tech unit was finally able
to restore the memory card

41:37.704 --> 41:39.539
on Wallace Yamashiro's
video camera.

41:39.539 --> 41:41.082
Our Bigfoot hunter.

41:41.082 --> 41:43.584
This video was on it.

41:43.584 --> 41:45.586
Um, okay.

41:45.586 --> 41:47.505
6:20 p. m.

41:47.505 --> 41:50.425
Uh, for years,
I've suffered the ridicule

41:50.425 --> 41:53.553
of my colleagues
and endured their taunts.

41:53.553 --> 41:55.013
Now I have my proof.

41:55.013 --> 42:04.772
♪♪

42:04.772 --> 42:06.357
Wait. That's --

42:06.357 --> 42:07.358
Skookum?

42:07.358 --> 42:08.568
Oh, my God.

42:08.568 --> 42:10.153
This can't be real,
right?

42:10.153 --> 42:11.696
Where was this taken?

42:11.696 --> 42:13.072
That's the thing.

42:13.072 --> 42:16.409
Wallace never says.

42:16.409 --> 42:19.162
And there is no G. P. S. function
on that camera.

42:21.873 --> 42:22.707
[ Creature roars ]

42:26.377 --> 42:29.380
-- Captions by VITAC --

42:29.380 --> 42:37.597
♪♪

42:37.597 --> 42:46.064
♪♪

